this is one of my chef instructors @iceculinary (Kathryn Gordon) demonstrating how to make a quenelle! we had some downtime in one of our previous classes so we whipped up some cream and were taught how make a one-handed quenelle (by the way she’s dipping the spoon in hot water). she mentioned how there are countless different ways to make quenelles, but this is the method she wanted to teach us! the way she demonstrated as always with chefs made it look so easy even though it’s definitely something you have to practice a few times before getting down. i thought this was a really great in depth tutorial so i wanted to share with all of you! if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me, and i hope you all make perfect quenelles after this :D

day 67 of culinary school @iceculinary is our pastry final! there’s a lot to get into so let’s get straight into it. the exam was simple by itself, making an almond raspberry tart we had made back in the first few classes of our pastry unit. but for the first time we weren’t separated into two groups which meant the kitchen was gonna be packed. i felt solid about everything so i got right into getting the dough and filling for my tart prepared before taking my written exam. the written exam was a bit more extensive and we hadnt reviewed much for it so it was more difficult than usual but i got through it (we haven’t gotten the grades back yet but i think i got above a 90??). then for finishing the tart it was a little bit stressful because with everyone opening the oven and finishing their written exams at different times it was hard to judge when you should check your tart yourself. i pulled them out though and felt really good about how they looked! then the unfortunate miscommunication about the frangipane recipe and in the moment i was pretty stressed about it, but looking back i still did my very best that day and that’s all that really matters. the pastry unit has been full of fun from day one and a huge step away from the savory things we have been doing, so i am excited to step back into some new international cuisines! want to thank you all so much for supporting, every course/module i finish just makes me think of how far we have come together, there is so much learning still to be had. and as always if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly :D

 #reels #culinary #culinaryarts #culinaryschool #culinarystudent #culinaryexperience #chef #food #cook #cooking #learn #learntocook #bake #baking #test #exam #grade #dayinthelife

day 68 @iceculinary is the beginning of international cuisine!! we are diving straight into the mediterranean and learning about all sorts of “traditional” dishes (i know some of these arent 100% traditional, it’s just the recipes the culinary school provides us). i mainly focused on kofte and dolma today, but other groups did things like the moussaka, gigantes plaki, among other recipes! i love mediterranean food so i was super excited to make everything. for international cuisine we are focusing on teamwork and ending the day with a big buffet where all the food should be finished all around the same time. it was a nice and simple first day and i am excited to learn more and more about other cuisines. as always if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me!

here is my pastry chef grading my baking final! i made a almond and raspberry tart and a strawberry almond tart (not shown) and had them graded by my chef.  if you haven’t watched the exam day video, what he’s talking about in the video is the filling for my tart. i made a double/triple recipe of frangipane because i wanted to make two tarts (just a personal challenge) what i didn’t know was that we were getting graded on making a very specific amount of filling from a recipe on a sheet of paper he handed out a few weeks ago. i had absolutely no clue that was how the test was getting graded, and so i was definitely confused by the grade i got, but at the end of the day it was my fault. in the end i think i made a great product and i learned so much this module that i would have never approached before. i am also so grateful for all of you following me through this whole journey, i hope you learned a lot from the pastry unit and we’re back to savory. as always if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly and happy friday and happy holidays!!

here were my favorite things i learned in our pastry/baking unit in culinary school @iceculinary !!! it was only three weeks of classes, but it was packed full of recipes and concepts to do. my favorites were the frangipane tart we made to begin and for our final, the pizza we made mostly because we had a fun time sharing slices with friends, the flan and panna cotta because they were just so delicious and one of my favorite sweet things we made, the challah bread because it came out so satisfyingly and it was our first time learning about yeast, then finally the focaccia simply because i had always wanted to make it and it was so satisfying dimpling it and then seeing it come out so perfectly! it was a great unit, had some ups and downs but i have improved a lot since we started which makes it all worth it. i hope you all enjoyed, i have to hustle to prep for a dinner party i have tonight so hope you all have a great christmas weekend, if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly! happy holidays everybody :D

merry christmas even everyone and here’s a quick look at the dinner party i threw for some friends yesterday! i had a lot of fun with this one, and especially nice for the holidays. did a french x chinese fusion and a full video will be out tonight! merry christmas to you all and if you don’t celebrate i still hope you are enjoying the holiday season as we approach the new year :D appreciate all of the support and i have some exciting updates to share with you as i am on my winter break from culinary school. hope everyone enjoys the weekend and all of your amazing dinners and plans!

merry christmas everyone!!!! and here is the chinese x french fusion dinner party i threw last night for the holidays! hope everyone is home or somewhere comfortable and relaxing. for the dinner i had 5 courses, 2 appetizers, 2 main entrees, and dessert! starting with hand-ripped chili noodles persillade. the persillade was so fragrant and sharp with the savory chili oil and fresh cucumber and arugula was honestly one of my favorite bites. then the spring rolls, from light and acidic straight to fatty and rich with the creamy truffle butter sauce. the first main was a chinese fish en papillote which i think was my most fun fusion idea, topped the bass with bok choy, eggplant, peppers, and nothing better than sharing a tasty broth and scallion steamed fish. then the duck with a pomelo reduction sauce and the edamame garlic puree (didn’t like the end plating all too much) was super balanced with all of it’s components. the final dish was fuji apple tarte tatin and i finally made a good dessert for one of my dinner parties. with the almond cookie whipped cream, it was so good. i had a lot of fun with this one and prepped and conceptualized it in the least amount of time so far! i really hope you all enjoyed, i hope youre enjoying time to yourself or with friends and family, if you have any questions feel free to comment below and merry merry merry christmas all 🎄🎄🎄

here are my favorite two pasta dishes that i made with my family for christmas!!! instead of a traditional dinner i decided we should do something new, and since my dad has been into italian food since visiting this summer what better than doing a little pasta making lesson for them. i prepped all of my sauces in advance that way we could make our pasta and have food right away! for the rest of the dinner i made some appetizers like eggplant with romesco, spanakopita, and a whole roast duck but the pasta we made was by far my favorite! hope you enjoy the video i just want to thank you all again and again for all of the support, hope you all are having a great christmas/new years and if you have any questions feel free to ask in the comments below or message me :D

BIG NEWS: my first ever trail at a restaurant ever!!! the last 2 months of my culinary school include an externship where we have to go out ourselves and get an internship it a restaurant of our choice. i just got 2 responses from michelin starred restaurants and i couldn’t be more excited and nervous (can you guess which two restaurants in NY?). just wanted to share with you all that have been following along this journey so far. it’s been a crazy few months and there are so many of you here that i hope continue to learn and experience this industry with me. as always if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me, happy holidays :D

happy 100 days everyone! on september 19th i started posting my culinary school videos and i could have never ever ever imagined how much you would all enjoy them. i starter posting because i had been making volleyball content and while i was taking a break wanted to do the same for my culinary journey. who knew it would be so fun explaining and documenting everything i have been learning and now i get to do it for over 140,000 of you. this video is a thank you and a little reminiscing on the very first cooking videos i used to make in my college apartment which i can’t even believe was a year ago. from learning how to hold a knife to creating recipes and being able to do so much more i hope you have been improving and enjoying cooking as much as i have these past few months. and i will always be grateful for those that have been here since the beginning and are still just joining. i am on a train to my first ever trail just months after really learning how to cook, and i am nervous and excited to keep on going with all of you! and as always, if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly, to many more hundreds of days ❤️

here is the recipe to the steak dish i made for our 100th day together! i tried to do something super simple so you could try the same, we have roast beets, sautéed beet stems/leaves, mashed potatoes, a garlic green pea puree, a pan-seared steak, and a beautiful balsamic pan sauce. so much has happened in the past few months and this fall and winter is passing so quickly. if you’re wondering about the trail, don’t worry i am going to do a video explaining exactly what happened very soon, and i still have my other trail tomorrow at… jean-georges! i’m going to the city today to enjoy a meal with someone special (actually at gramercy tavern hahaha) and i think for the new years you should cook something tasty for whoever you have in your life that just makes things better whether that’s friends, family, or someone in particular. as always if you have any questions feel free to ask in the comments below or message me directly! looking forward to the new year :D

here’s a demonstration from one of my chefs at culinary school (Richard Kennedy) taught us to make a pizza! just a disclaimer this is his own method, and most definitely not the only way, just wanted to share his method for stretching his pizza dough. we also only had pretty small pizza plates and large balls of dough so our pizzas were relatively thick crust (not my preferred hahaha). i know this is a bit random but wanted to share since i have been really tired and busy traveling in and out of the city for my trails these past few days. i will hopefully share with you guys how they went tomorrow or for the new years! hope you guys enjoy, and as always if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly. thanks so much for the support, i’m focusing up for my trails and just doing my very best :D

here is everything i made for my dinner party last night! the concept was japanese french fusion and i had a menu of tempura, onigiri (kinda), udon, steak, and creme caramel. this was such a fun menu to create and i was really happy because i was stressing thinking about ideas when i thought of the confit duck onigiri and then the rest of the dish ideas started coming in. the tempura was served with a miso honey hollandaise, a little tangy but nice and sweet with the umami of the miso. the onigiri unfortunately fell apart so i changed the dish and ended up serving it in a miso soup to save it. the udon was mixed with a lot of crab and mussels in a play on sauce americaine (this is the stock i made a couple nights ago). then there was my favorite savory dish the steak with yakiniku sauce, almost smokey from the toasted sesame flavor and balanced perfectly with the wasabi sauce. last was dessert and i finally got it to taste great, plating still needed a lot of work though hahaha. super fun dinner, had lots of fun with this one even though the presentation didn’t turn out well, but hopefully just getting better and better for the next! hope you all enjoy and as always if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly! hope you all had a great weekend and i will see you soon :D

day 73 is more international cuisine and we are learning about food from South America and the Caribbean! today i pretty much just made the ceviche and then helped anyone who needed hands with their own recipes so it was super chill. the ceviche we made was with snapper and the leche de tigre that we made was so tasty with a serious punch of citrus flavor. other people made dishes like feijoada and farofa a stew and topping from brazil, tostones, codfish and rice, and aji de gallons (which i wanted to do hahaha). overall everything was delicious with a variety of different flavors and textures. again sorry if i mispronounce or the recipes don’t do the culture justice, just doing my best to learn and follow the curriculum they show us. hope you all enjoyed and if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly, and i hope you all have a great start to your week :D

day 74 of culinary school @iceculinary is a fun one since we are cooking food from India! with so many regions and different techniques to learn we made dishes like lamb and chicken curry, pakora, various pulao, samosas, shrimp, and sea bass. i specifically worked on the chicken korma and mango lassi today. it was cool learning more in depth about the differences in cuisine from south to northern India and i thought i did a really good job making my chicken korma today. still a bit sad i didnt get to chow down but i learned lots of useful information and hope you all liked learning about it as well! as always if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly :D

day 76 of culinary school @iceculinary and we are making my favorites dumplings!! i was so excited tor today because i knew it wouldn’t be too heavy on the dishes and we would be making all sorts of wrapped stuff which I love to make but really suck at making look pretty. i was assigned the potstickers which i was happy about and it started with shredding a bunch of cabbage and letting all of the water come out (we ground everything together later to get a more consistent filling). it was a nice and relaxing day just wrapping things and i got to go around and make everything at least once. we also made a bunch extra for a special event which was fun because other people would be eating our dumplings! very good day of practice for me today and the potstickers tasted great which i was happy about. hope you all enjoyed, as always feel free to comment below if you have any questions or message me directly, hope you have fun things planned for the weekend, because i have some exciting stuff to share!!

this is a dish i used to make inspired by niangao (and also a twist on my sister’s recipe) every week in college because it was cheap and made so much food i could eat it for dinner and have leftovers for the next day. i know i excluded sesame oil and soy sauce because they are staples in my pantry and i don’t even think about restocking them. im sure it is also pretty unlikely you are buying a singular potato or head of garlic for your recipes, but if you wanted to make this dish it would only set you back around 10 dollars and it is so quick and easy i was able to do it in my dorm before i went to culinary school or knew anything about cooking really. i’ll put a rough recipe down below but the video shows most of it and the measurements for soy sauce and sesame oil are mostly to taste since they’re the main flavorings for the dish! if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly, I actually have a few trails set up for this weekend so gonna rest up and see you in the next :D

niangao recipe (untraditional):
1 chicken quarter (trimmed, diced)
salt & pepper (lightly seasoned, salt mostly from soy sauce)
soy sauce (a few tbsp)
sesame oil (a few tbsp)
3 cloves garlic (minced)

3 bok choy heads (picked and washed)
1 potato (sliced, anyway preferred)
1/2 onion (saute slice)
1 pack rice cakes (any variety/shape)

soy sauce to finish (a few tbsp to 1/2 cup)
sesame oil to finish (a drizzle)

optional: 
shaoxing cooking wine for marinade
corn starch slurry to thicken

day 77 of culinary school @iceculinary and we are making food from Thailand! continuing our international cuisine days is an especially exciting one because our chef (Chayanin “Nin” Pornsriniyom) is from Thailand. we learned about all sorts of traditional ingredients and how theyre used, then i got to make a green coconut curry. often times in Thai cuisine the spices and aromatics are ground into a paste before being added to coconut milk or other flavored bases which shows off the many influences on Thailand from its neighboring countries. once i made my paste and had all of my ingredients it was just a matter of putting everything together (i wish i had a little more curry paste) and the end result was delicious. i had a lot of fun learning today and i hope you all enjoyed. sorry for the late post today i’ve been slammed with work and prep since i have a bunch of videos planned and a trail coming up tomorrow actually. as always if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly. hope you all have exciting things planned for the weekend :D

this recipe i made for my last dinner party was so good i had to make it again! it’s a matcha creme caramel which is similar to a flan and also extremely easy to make. all it takes is 5 ingredients and you could actually flavor this however you want as long as you mix it in properly with the base flavors! creamy custardy, but make sure to be careful with how much caramel you add otherwise you might end up with a hardened top bit. super tasty, so so fun to pop open (cut around the edges, then release by puncturing the mold) great for friends and family or just for yourself! the recipe below yielded about 18 of those small circular muffin molds that i used in this video so you can definitely scale down if you are cooking for less (or i prefer just making them larger hahaha). hope you all are having an amazing weekend and if you have any questions at all feel free to comment below or message me!

diluted caramel:

sugar 450g
lemon juice 5g (optional)
water 60g

mixture for baked custards:

half and half 975g
sugar 225g
large eggs 200g (4 large eggs)
egg yolks 135g (6-7 eggs)
vanilla extract 15g
matcha powder 20-30g (can be replaced for other flavorings or left out if you just want vanilla custard)

an exciting day @iceculinary as we tackle Vietnamese and Filipino food! so sorry if i butcher any pronunciation and if the recipes aren’t 100% authentic just following as best i can. today we did all sorts of dishes and i was happy to make the chicken adobo since i’ve never had and always heard a lot about it (though i feel like this recipe isn’t exactly correct but i may be wrong). also got to make some lumpia and watch others grill steak for rice noodle salads, make braised fish, and all sorts of great plates of food! a fun day cooking a recipe from a cuisine that i really like but havent had all too often and it was cool seeing some more dishes than the mainstream ones out there. if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly :D

day 79 of culinary school is sushi day!!! i absolutely love sushi so was super excited for us to take a visit to Japan and make some sushi. we also made some soba and tamago but those were really on the side items as we prepped our vegetables fish and rice for sushi! sushi is all about the rice and i was happy to make a huge batch for half the class to use seasoning with rice wine vinegar salt and sugar for that classic sushi rice taste and using an hangiri for the first time which was super fun. the method of making sushi is really simple but might share anyways for all of you to learn since i thought it was a good demonstration. hope you all enjoyed learning about all the different types of sushi (which i definitely didn’t know all of them). if you have any questions feel free to comment below or message me directly :D
